      • isCached

        public boolean isCached(BuildContext context)
        Description copied from interface: BuildRule
        A rule is considered "cached" if it satisfies all of the following criteria:
        1. the output file for this rule exists
        2. all of the dependencies for this rule are cached
        3. the output file was created using precisely the same dependencies, which in turn have precisely the same state as when the output file was created
        A rule that is cached should not be rebuilt.

        Note that it is always safe for this method to return false; however, that may result in unnecessary rebuilding.

        Specified by:
        isCached in interface BuildRule

      • hasUncachedDescendants

        public boolean hasUncachedDescendants(BuildContext context)
                               throws IOException
        Description copied from interface: BuildRule
        A rule is considered to have uncached descendants if it satisfies any of the following criteria:
        1. this rule is uncached as determined by BuildRule.isCached(BuildContext)
        2. any of the dependencies for this rule have uncached descendants.
        Some build rules only need to be rebuilt if some subset of their dependencies are uncached vs. if any of their descendants are uncached. Other rules (like packaging rules) need to run if any of their descendants are uncached.

        Note that it is always safe for this method to return true; however, that may result in unnecessary rebuilding.

        Specified by:
        hasUncachedDescendants in interface BuildRule
        Throws:
        IOException

      • ruleKeyBuilder

        public RuleKey.Builder ruleKeyBuilder()
        getRuleKey() calls the most derived implementation of this method to lazily construct a RuleKey. Every subclass that extends the rule state in a way that matters to idempotency must override ruleKeyBuilder() and append its state to the RuleKey.Builder returned by its superclass's ruleKeyBuilder() implementation.

      • getRuleKey

        public final RuleKey getRuleKey()
        Description copied from interface: BuildRule
        If the resulting RuleKey is non-idempotent, it must not be internally memoized -- subsequent calls to getRuleKey() must re-evaluate the BuildRule's transitive state. Under normal operating conditions non-idempotent RuleKeys may arise due to not-yet-generated outputs. With careful ordering of execution planning versus RuleKey generation it is usually possible to avoid the creation of non-idempotent RuleKeys. However, dependency graph construction/evaluation would need to be incremental in order to reliably maintain an invariant which would allow blind RuleKey memoization.
        Specified by:
        getRuleKey in interface BuildRule
        Returns:
        key based on the BuildRule's state, including the transitive closure of its dependencies' keys.
